Hibernate lets you decide the depth of fetches in case of `EAGER` fetches in your Entity classes.

Consider an example:

````
public class ClassA implements Serializable{
@JoinColumn(name=&quot;class_b&quot;, referenceColumnName=&quot;id&quot;)
@ManyToOne
private ClassB classB;
}

public class ClassB implements Serializable{
@JoinColumn(name=&quot;class_c&quot;, referenceColumnName=&quot;id&quot;)
@ManyToOne
private ClassC classC;
}

public class ClassC implements Serializable{
@JoinColumn(name=&quot;class_d&quot;, referenceColumnName=&quot;id&quot;)
@ManyToOne
private ClassD classD;
}


public class ClassD implements Serializable{
//codes
}
````

If you  fetch ClassA, and your `hibernate.max_fetch_depth` is set to 2, it will only ClassB and then classB will fetch ClassC and the fetching  process is terminated.

You can look at this [Document](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/stable/core.old/reference/en/html/configuration-optional.html) for more information.

